      "id":"commentisfree/2013/nov/05/toronto-mayor-resign-rob-ford-crack-allegations",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-05T16:32:31Z",
      "webTitle":"Toronto's mayor completes the city's humiliation by refusing to resign | Heather Mallick",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/05/toronto-mayor-resign-rob-ford-crack-allegations",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/05/toronto-mayor-resign-rob-ford-crack-allegations",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Heather Mallick: </strong>Crack allegations, drunken behaviour and bad company have all failed to unseat Rob Ford. 'Moving forward', what are the lessons for other cities?</p>",
        "headline":"Toronto's mayor completes the city's humiliation by refusing to resign",
        "body":"<video data-media-id=\"gu-video-421601739\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"\">\n        <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/11/04/131104Canada-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/11/04/131104Canada_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/11/04/131104Canada_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/11/05/131104Canada/131104Canada.m3u8\"></source>\n      </video><p>Toronto's humiliation is complete. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/03/toronto-mayor-rob-ford-apologises\" title=\"\">Its mayor, Rob Ford, won't resign</a>. Torontonians gathered around their news devices on a Sunday afternoon to hear Ford take the high road on talk radio – it was like a version of Brits waiting for Chamberlain to get back from Munich, except terribly stupid – and we learned several things.</p><p>\"<a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/rob-ford-apologizes-for-mistakes-but-won-t-step-down-1.2335939\" title=\"\">I am not a rat</a>,\" the internationally ridiculed mayor said. \"I'm not an addict of any type of drug, even alcohol. I'm not an alcoholic.\"</p><p>Canadians don't do interventions. That's an American thing. But you see why we don't bother? A nice 81-year-old lady begged Ford on air to take a medical leave, and he patronised her infinitely. She wasn't talking about the lies or the criminal associates. She just meant the yelling and the way Ford collides with things on camera: <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MzI72WrOeA0 a football, http://blogs.shawconnect.ca/breaktime/rob-fords-football-follies-immortalized-in-gif-form/\" title=\"\">a weighing scale</a>, <a href=\"http://imgur.com/nATPNJb\" title=\"\">another camera</a>.</p><p>Then the mayor, who has been under surveillance for months by police in aeroplanes and cars and from cameras attached to poles, said he aims not to get \"hammered\" in public any more and agreed with his brother and fellow city councillor Doug Ford that it's best just to have a few \"pops\" in one's basement. The <a href=\" http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sandro-lisi-who-is-rob-ford-s-friend-and-driver-1.2304355\" title=\"\">photos of him meeting a man with a criminal history</a> – who has since been charged with extortion – in gas stations and parking lots, and his hundreds of phone conversations with that man? It didn't really come up.</p><p>Ford had no comment on the contents of the notorious video taken of him allegedly smoking crack with Somali-Canadian gang members (Dixon City Bloods) and making homophobic and racist slurs, a video that he had previously claimed didn't exist. All he asked was that the <a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sandro-lisi-who-is-rob-ford-s-friend-and-driver-1.2304355\" title=\"\">police release the videos (plural) of him</a> – including the one that the city's police chief had said, with a sigh from the sonared depths, had made him feel \"disappointed\" – and he would continue to be the \"best mayor Toronto has ever had\".</p><p>He had only one request for the media: \"Don't stand on my driveway.\" I should say here that Ford sees the newspaper I work for, the Toronto Star, as his greatest enemy. Ford has called for a boycott of the Star, edited by a determined Brit named Michael Cooke, and will not speak to its reporters. The Star was taken to a <a href=\"http://ontpress.com/2013/10/16/opc-decision-donley-vs-toronto-star-october-2013/\" title=\"\">press complaints commission for its reporting and was entirely vindicated</a>.</p><p>Ford used that deadly piece of jargon, \"moving forward,\" dozens of times and so shall I. Toronto doesn't want your pity. (Actually, we do. We want a massively undeserved hug.) We want to make sure you don't repeat our mistakes.</p><p>First, do not artificially enlarge your city. A 1998 decision by the hard-right provincial government to amalgamate Toronto's downtown with its sprawling suburbs meant that voters had little in common with each other. If you vote out of spite, envy and revenge, this is the mayor you get.</p><p>Second, have a fast legal means of removing an elected official from office. Toronto does not have one. Ford does not have to depart until he is taken from a courtroom in handcuffs to jail.</p><p>Third, keep your police force independent of elected officials. Ford is going to decide the budget of the police force that has been investigating him for months, while weirdly failing to question him even once.</p><p>Fourth, if you're going to vote for a man who drinks, choose your candidate as carefully as you would the uncle you're having over for Christmas dinner. An affable drunk is always preferable to a habitually aggrieved one. No shoving! No throwing footballs indoors! No <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2013/11/01/rob_ford_very_intoxicated_at_city_hall_night_of_st_patricks_day_2012.html\" title=\"\">calling the cops to say your car's been stolen</a> because you can't find it!</p><p>Fifth ... oh, the hell with it. We're sorry about our sinister prime minister, Stephen Harper, not believing in global warming or indeed science. But Ford? We did it to ourselves. Have a hearty laugh at our expense.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421717175|2013-11-05T17:53:02Z|4c8303e6436fcab34e1307d8eb2d5f3994615b4c -->",
